amptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1168–":"about 1168–Deceased","1165–Male":"1165–Deceased","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1168–Female":"1168–Deceased","Abt 1184":"about 1184","ABT 1185":"about 1185","Abt 1168":"about 1168","1168":"1168","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","Of,,, England":"England, United Kingdom","Of, Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Brooks","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually a variant of   Brook  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>. The optional addition of <i>-s</i>, with no grammatical function, is usually post-medieval, but some examples of the same person's name occurring with and without <i>-(e)s</i> have been noted as early as the 14th century in South Lancashire. The <i>-es</i> in such cases probably has neither a plural nor a genitival function, and the name means ‘dweller at the brook’, not ‘dweller at the brooks’. A plural sense cannot be ruled out elsewhere, but a non-grammatical <i>-(e)s</i> must also be considered a strong possibility.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Brucks  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brucks","meanings":["North German:","probably a habitational name from Brucks (also Brux) which derives from Middle Low German <i>brōk</i> ‘low-lying marsh’.","reportedly also an altered form of Flemish (Dutch) <b>Broex</b>, an old variant of <b>Broeks</b> (see   Brooks  )."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Brookes","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Brooks  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs- William Brooks was born about 1168, in Oakley, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Brooks about 1184, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1168–":"umbes 1168–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","Abt 1184":"umbes 1184","ABT 1185":"umbes 1185","Abt 1168":"umbes 1168","1168":"1168","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","Of,,, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1168–":"noin 1168–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1168–Female":"1168–Kuollut","Abt 1184":"noin 1184","ABT 1185":"noin 1185","Abt 1168":"noin 1168","1168":"1168","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","Of,,, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of, Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshir